ticular jobs are structured and changed over time, the role of workers' resistance and trade unions in shaping the lives of workers, and the impact of technology. Together these essays clarify a fundamental characteristic shared by all labour processes: they are shaped and conditioned by the social, economic, and political struggles of labour and capital both inside and outside the workplace. They argue that technological change, as well as all the transformations in the workplace, must become a social process that we all control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndustrial relationszCanadaxHistory. 0aIndustrial sociologyzCanadaxHistory. 0aWorkxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh1 aCraven, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, John Bellamy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeron, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKealey, Gregory S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowe, Graham S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadforth, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReiter, Ester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteedman, Mercedes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorey, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong-Boag, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTraves, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWells, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/